You gotta remember the, uh, the humans floating
in vats of KY jelly?

5
00:00:15,910 --> 00:00:19,820
Tubes and wires keeping them alive, stimulating
their brains, to make them believe that they

6
00:00:19,820 --> 00:00:23,660
were experiencing the real world – the world
we all think we know?

7
00:00:23,660 --> 00:00:28,700
Well, almost-20-year-old spoiler alert here: some of
them come to find out that the real world was a

8
00:00:28,700 --> 00:00:33,220
desolate wasteland, and the lives everyone thought they were living were just fabrications fed into their brains.

9
00:00:33,220 --> 00:00:37,920
A select few were ‘rescued’ from the illusion,
but some of them were so unhappy in the real

10
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:40,399
world that they chose to return to illusion.

11
00:00:40,399 --> 00:00:44,159
But Neo -- and the others who chose to stay
and fight --- were the philosophical heroes

12
00:00:44,159 --> 00:00:47,599
of the movie, choosing truth at the cost of
comfort and happiness.

13
00:00:47,600 --> 00:00:51,380
After watching The Matrix, you might’ve
found yourself wondering: Could this be true?

14
00:00:51,389 --> 00:00:55,940
Could we possibly be stuck in a dream world
of someone else’s making, with no way to

15
00:00:55,940 --> 00:00:58,489
tell that our “reality” isn’t real at
all?

16
00:00:58,489 --> 00:01:01,499
If so, you’re not the first person to have
wondered about these things.

17
00:01:01,499 --> 00:01:05,779
In fact, the original Neo? The guy who really
went into battle against the matrix of illusion,

18
00:01:05,780 --> 00:01:07,359
in order to defend the Truth?

19
00:01:07,360 --> 00:01:10,540
He was a 17th century mathematician. Named
Rene.

20
00:01:10,540 --> 00:01:20,660
